<subsection xml:id="subsec-Formation_of_algebraic_expressions_from_simple_algebraic_statements_involving_addition_and_subtraction">
  <title>Formation of algebraic expressions from simple algebraic statements , involving addition and subtraction.</title>
  <activity>
    <p> <em>Work in groups</em> </p>
    <p>
      Karisa buys mangoes from a kiosk.He then buys two more mangoes from another kiosk.
    </p>
      <p>
                    <ol marker="i)">
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Use a letter to represent the number of mangoes Karisa bought from the first kiosk.
                        </p>
                      </li>

                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Write down an algebraic expression for the total number of mangoes Karisa bought.
                        </p>
                      </li>

                      <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss and share with other groups.
                        </p>
                      </li>
                      
                    </ol>
                  </p>
  </activity>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Mwangi is <m>6</m> years older than Otieno If Otieno’s age is <m>X</m> years, write down an algebraic expression for Mwangi’s age.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Mwangi’s age = <m>(x+6)</m>  years.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-Formation_of_algebraic_expressions_from_simple_algebraic_statements_involving_multiplication_and_division">
  <title>Formation of algebraic expressions from simple algebraic statements involving multiplication and division</title>
  <example>
  <statement>
    <p>
       Form an algebraic expression for the number of hours in <m>t</m> days.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      The number of hours in <m>1 = 24</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Thus the number of hours in <m>t  days = 24t</m>
    </p>
  </solution>   
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
      <m>100</m> members of a group are given <m>r</m> tree seedlings to share equally. Form an algebraic expression for the number of seedlings each member gets.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Each member gets <m> \frac{r}{100}</m> seedlings.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</subsection>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-Simplification_of_algebraic_expressions_in_real_life_situations">
  <title>Simplification of algebraic expressions in real life situations</title>
  <activity>
  <p> <em>Work in groups</em> </p>
    <p>
      <ol marker="i">
        <li>
          <p>
            Consider a mathematical set costing <m>n</m> shillings and a textbook costing <m>250</m> shillings more than the set.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Form an algebraic expression for the cost of a textbook.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Form and simplify an algebraic expression for the total cost of <m>2</m> mathematical sets and <m>3</m> textbooks.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Discuss and compare your expressions with other groups.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </activity>
  <p>
  <em>Learning point:</em>
  </p>
  <p>
    Simplification in algebra involves putting like terms together.
  </p>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Joseph initially had <m>y</m> shillings . He spent <m>2000</m> shillings.James has twice what Joseph is left with. Form an algebraic expression for the total amount of money they both have.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Joseph has <m>y - 2000</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        James has <m>2(y - 2000)</m>
      </p>
      <p>
       <m>=2y - 4000</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        The total amount in shillings.
      </p>
      <p>
        \qquad <m>=y - 2000 + y - 4000</m>
      </p>
      <p>
                <m>=y + y - 2000 - 4000</m>
      </p>
      <p>
                <m>=3y - 6000 </m>

      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Konyango bought <m>x</m> sheep at <m>2500</m> shillings each.He also bought goats which were <m>y </m> less than the number of sheep at <m>3000</m> shillings each. Form an algebraic expression for the total amount of money Konyango spent on the animals.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The amount spent on <m>x</m> sheep was <m>KSh 2 500x</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        On goats,he spent <m>KSh 3000(x - y)</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        The total amount <m>=Ksh 2500x + Ksh 3000x - Ksh 300y</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        \qquad <m>=Ksh 5500x - Ksh 3000y</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  
</subsection>
